column2:
Probability of an asymptomatic 
infection with no prior immunity
column4:
Value obtained from a 
simulation study which simulated probability of clinical infection in the range (80,100)

column2:
1/Latent period 
of infection
column4:
This paper quotes the onset 
of infection to be 10-15 days so 12.5 days is used

column2:
Probability of an asymptomatic 
infection upon re-infection
column4: Taken as the percentage of all P. vivax infected individuals that were and remained asymptomatic throughout 2 cross-sectional household surveys in Brazil

column2: Probability of treatment seeking if clinically infected
column4:
Observed and predicted treatment
seeking rate using national-level predictions. Taken as the midpoint of Venezuela (50-55%)for the "any treatment" seeking map

column2: Rate of treatment seeking (1/average number of days to seek treatment since symptoms began)
column4:
Taken as the mean number of days 
to consultation for a P. vivax infected individual

column2: Rate of loss of symptoms from clinical infection to asymptomatic infection
column4:
Taken as the 1/ average duration 
of symptoms in an untreated clinical infection. Obtained from a simulation study (the first attached source) which simulated in the range (2,60)

column2: Probability of recovery with hypnozoites following PQ+CQ treatment
column4: Assumed from an expert opinion presented in this paper by Michael T. White. The efficacy value includes the effect of poor adherence to treatment plan

column2: Rate of recovery following asymptomatic infection with no treatment (1/average number of days to recover since symptoms began)
column4:
Taken as the 1/ average duration 
of symptoms in an untreated symptomatic infection. Obtained from a simulation study (the first attached source) which simulated in the range (60,200)

column2: Rate of loss of protection against reinfection following 3 days of CQ treatment
column4:
Taken as 1/ the remaining 
prophylatic period of CQ following the loss of infectiousness (37 days). An individual is protected against reinfection for this period

column2: Rate of relapse
column4:
1/average number of days 
taken to relapse following end of treatment plan

column2: Probability of asymptomatic infection if relapsing
column4:
Taken as the percentage 
of all recurrent P.vivax infections that occurred within a year which were asymptomatic

column2:
Probability of relapse if 
recovered with hypnozoites
column4: Taken as the percentage of P. vivax infected individuals that re-presented with P. vivax within 30 days of any dose of PQ (no PQ, low dose PQ, high dose PQ). Any dose group was used instead of just the low dose PQ group since in the model, those who do not receive treatment can also relapse

column2: Rate of death of hypnozoites
column4:
1/average number of 
days for a hypnozoite to die

column2: Rate of loss of immunity following recovery if not re-infected
column4:
Value obtained from a 
simulation study which simulated immunity in the range (0.5,10) years

column2: Test sensitivity
column4:
Taken as the weighted mean
of microscopy and RDT test
sensitivity using available
data on proportion of
infections diagnosed using
microscopy or RDT testing.
The available data on
diagnostic methods shows
91.16% of tests were microscopy
(test sens =0.957) and 8.84%
were RDT (test sens=0.87) so
test sensitivity was taken to
be 0.9116*(0.957) + 0.0884*
(0.87) = 0.94031

column2: Importation rate
column4: Assumed using naïve model fitting methods. This rate to be simulated within an appropiate range using  bayesian model calibration techniques

column2: Proportion of imported individuals that are clinical
column4: Taken as (1-pa2) since we assume that imported individuals have probabilities of being asymptomatic and clinical equal to the probabilities of asymptomatic and clinical infection upon reinfection. This is since imported individuals are likely coming from highly endemic regions such as Bolivar and have thus likely been previously infected

column2: Proportion of imported individuals that are asymptomatic
column4: Taken as pa2 since we assume that imported individuals have probabilities of being asymptomatic and clinical equal to the probabilities of asymptomatic and clinical infection upon reinfection. This is since imported individuals are likely coming from highly endemic regions such as Bolivar and have thus likely been previously infected

column2: Probability of sleeping under a net
column4: Taken as the average proportion of individuals who slept under a net the previous night in the study

column2: Effectiveness of LLIN reducing infectious bites
column4: Taken as the overall risk reduction for reducing malarira by LLIN use

column2: Number of people who sleep under one LLIN net
column4: Master plan for strengthening the HIV, tuberculosis and malaria response in the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela from a public health perspective - 2018

column2:
Human feeding rate
per mosquito per week
column4: This paper quotes 0.21 bites per day so this value is scaled by a factor of 7 to get in terms of weeks

column2:
Transmission efficacy from
mosquito to human
column4: Taken as the proportion of infected individuals out of the total number of individuals challenged with one bite

column2:
Transmission efficacy from
human to mosquito
column4: Taken as the proportion of infected subjects which led to infection in mosquitos

column2: Density of mosquitos
column4: Assumed using naïve model fitting methods

column2: Death rate of mosquitos
column4:
This paper quotes a death rate 
of 0.1 per day so this has been scaled by a factor of 7 to get in terms of weeks

column2: Latent period in mosquitos
column4:
1/ average number of days for 
a mosquito to become infectious following infection with P. vivax

column2: Importation switch
column4:
Switch to turn on and off importation
 in the model

column2: Scaling factor for FOI applied due to uncertainty in many of transmission parameters
column4:
To be determined more robustly
during model fitting

column2:
Relative infectivity of treated
patients
column4:
It was found after 3 days of CQ treatment
 in the study, these individuals were not infectious

column2:
Relative infectivity of asymptomatic
patients
column4:
Taken as the infectivity of 
asymptomatic individuals to An. Aquasalis over the infectivity of symptomatic individuals

column2:
Loss of infectiousness once 
treatment starts
column4: Taken as 1/3 days (scaled into weeks) since CQ treatment is 3 days long and this is when they lose infectiousness

column2:
Prophylatic period for 
chloroquine if non-infected
column4:
Taken as the mean quoted between each paper. In the first paper, the middle value
between 20 and 60 days - 40 days - is used. In the second paper, 1-2 months is quoted and so 45 days is used. The third paper quotes 45-55 so 50 days is used. This represents the period that an individual is protected against infection due to MDA treatment (in particular CQ treatment)

column2:

column4:
TQ is a single dose so taken as 
1 day
